The paper deals with the complexity of solving timed parity games, which is a topic in logic and automata theory (cs.LO). It also discusses strategies for real-time synthesis problems, which involves game theory and control theory (cs.GT, cs.SY). The paper presents a reduction of timed parity games to turn-based finite-state parity games, which involves graph theory and algorithms (cs.DS). The paper also discusses clock regions and timed automaton games, which are topics in formal methods and programming languages (cs.PL). Overall, the paper covers a wide range of topics in computer science, but the focus on logic, automata theory, and game theory suggests that cs.LO and cs.GT are the most likely sub-categories.
